ve herbivorous species whose effects appear to be less dramatic. Furthermore, the spatial and temporal variability in the structure of damselfish communities is largely unknown, further restricting our ability to make valid generalisations. While the effects of tenitoriality have been tested by damselfish removals, more sophisticated experimental work is needed to assess the relative contributions of selective feeding, reduced herbivory, weeding and other farming activities. These mechanisms will be clearer if we have a better understanding of the function of telTitoriality, the actual benefits of algal turfs to the damselfishes and the separate tasks involved with establishing and maintaining territories. Introduction},
